### Option 1: Generate a 3D House using Python & Three.js

This script creates a simple house with a roof, walls, and a door.

**Prerequisites:**
1.  Install Python.
2.  Install the `pywebview` library:
    ```bash
    pip install pywebview
    ```

**The Python Code (`house_generator.py`):**

```python
import pywebview

html_content = """
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <meta charset="utf-8">
    <title>3D House Model</title>
    <style>
        body { margin: 0; overflow: hidden; background-color: #87CEEB; }
        canvas { display: block; }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <!-- Load Three.js from CDN -->
    <script src="https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/three.js/r128/three.min.js"></script>
    <script>
        // 1. Scene Setup
        const scene = new THREE.Scene();
        scene.background = new THREE.Color(0x87CEEB); // Sky blue

        const camera = new THREE.PerspectiveCamera(75, window.innerWidth / window.innerHeight, 0.1, 1000);
        const renderer = new THREE.WebGLRenderer({ antialias: true });
        renderer.setSize(window.innerWidth, window.innerHeight);
        document.body.appendChild(renderer.domElement);

        // 2. Lighting
        const ambientLight = new THREE.AmbientLight(0xffffff, 0.6);
        scene.add(ambientLight);

        const directionalLight = new THREE.DirectionalLight(0xffffff, 0.8);
        directionalLight.position.set(10, 20, 10);
        scene.add(directionalLight);

        // 3. Materials
        const wallMaterial = new THREE.MeshLambertMaterial({ color: 0x8B4513 }); // Brown
        const roofMaterial = new THREE.MeshLambertMaterial({ color: 0x800000 }); // Dark Red
        const grassMaterial = new THREE.MeshLambertMaterial({ color: 0x228B22 }); // Green
        const doorMaterial = new THREE.MeshLambertMaterial({ color: 0x000000 }); // Black

        // 4. Geometry Construction
        const houseGroup = new THREE.Group();

        // Walls
        const wallGeometry = new THREE.BoxGeometry(10, 6, 8);
        const walls = new THREE.Mesh(wallGeometry, wallMaterial);
        houseGroup.add(walls);

        // Roof (Pyramid)
        const roofGeometry = new THREE.ConeGeometry(8, 4, 4);
        const roof = new THREE.Mesh(roofGeometry, roofMaterial);
        roof.position.y = 8; // Lift roof up
        houseGroup.add(roof);

        // Door
        const doorGeometry = new THREE.BoxGeometry(2, 4, 0.5);
        const door = new THREE.Mesh(doorGeometry, doorMaterial);
        door.position.set(0, 1, 4); // Center on front face
        houseGroup.add(door);

        // Ground (Grass)
        const groundGeometry = new THREE.PlaneGeometry(100, 100);
        const ground = new THREE.Mesh(groundGeometry, grassMaterial);
        ground.rotation.x = -Math.PI / 2;
        scene.add(ground);

        // Add House to Scene
        scene.add(houseGroup);

        // 5. Camera Position
        camera.position.set(15, 15, 15);
        camera.lookAt(0, 3, 0);

        // 6. Animation Loop
        function animate() {
            requestAnimationFrame(animate);

            // Rotate house slowly
            houseGroup.rotation.y += 0.005;

            renderer.render(scene, camera);
        }

        // Handle Window Resize
        window.addEventListener('resize', () => {
            camera.aspect = window.innerWidth / window.innerHeight;
            camera.updateProjectionMatrix();
            renderer.setSize(window.innerWidth, window.innerHeight);
        });

        animate();
    </script>
</body>
</html>
"""

# Create the window
window = pywebview.create_window('3D House Model', width=800, height=600)
window.load_html(html_content)
```

**How to run it:**
1.  Save the code above as `house_generator.py`.
2.  Open your terminal/command prompt.
3.  Run the script: `python house_generator.py`.
4.  A window will pop up showing your rotating 3D house.

